<div id="materials" class="section level4">
<h4><strong>Materials</strong></h4>
<p>The questionnaire consisted of demographic items (Tables 1, 2 and 3). Following this were 25 items assessing participants’ self-esteem on specific domains (DSSE), concluding with 1 item measuring global self-esteem (GSE) and 1 measuring openness to experience (OTE).</p>
<p>DSSE items aimed to capture self-evaluations on a number of domains, such as academic competence (e.g. item 17: “When I succeed on an assessment, I feel a sense of self-pride.”) and physical health (e.g. item 25 “Eating unhealthy foods makes me feel bad about myself”). Despite drawing influence from them, the present DSSE scale also aimed to expand on similar pre-existing scales <span class="citation">(e.g. Contingencies of Self-worth Scale, Crocker, Luhtanen, Cooper &amp; Bouvrette, 2003; Body-Self Relations Questionnaire, Brown, Cash &amp; Mikulka, 1990)</span> by including items related to social media (e.g. item 5: “Whenever my follower count goes down, my self-esteem suffers”), increasingly relevant to students and non-students alike in contemporary society <span class="citation">(Midgley, Thai, Lockwood, Kovacheff &amp; Page-Gould, 2021; Statista, 2022)</span>, potentially enhancing ecological validity of results by asking questions with more relevance to the sample <span class="citation">(e.g. Szczygieł, 2021)</span>. DSSE items were rated on a 5-point Likert scale assessing participant agreement, where 1 = “Strongly disagree” and 5 = “Strongly agree.” To reduce acquiescent responding <span class="citation">(Winkler, Kanouse &amp; Ware, 1982)</span>, item phrasing was balanced such that 11 items were phrased positively (e.g. item 17), 11 negatively phrased (e.g. item 5), and 3 phrased neutrally (e.g. item 2: “My self-esteem is influenced by how well I get along with others”).</p>
<p>GSE and OTE items were derived from Robins, Hendin and Trzesniewski <span class="citation">(2001)</span> and Gosling, Rentfrow and Swann <span class="citation">(2003)</span>, respectively. These similarly used a 5-point Likert scale, however participants instead rated to what extent they felt statements described them (1 = “Does not describe me” and 5 = “Describes me extremely well”). GSE and OTE items were positively phrased. Furthermore, whilst the Likert scale for DSSE items was balanced around a neutral midpoint (3 = “Neither agree nor disagree”), GSE and OTE scales represented a gradient of positive identification with the statement, with no neutral midpoint (3 = “Describes me moderately well”). Despite this difference, the use of midpoints in each scale also contributes to reducing acquiescent responding <span class="citation">(Tourangeau et al., 2000, cited in Podsakoff, MacKenzie, Lee &amp; Podsakoff, 2003)</span>.</p>
</div>
<div id="procedure" class="section level4">
<h4><strong>Procedure</strong></h4>
<p>Participants were provided a link via social media platforms to the questionnaire on Qualtrics software <span class="citation">(Qualtrics, Provo, UT, 2022)</span>. Pre-completion, participants were informed they were taking part in a short 10-minute study aiming to develop a questionnaire that captures subjective self-evaluations of different life-aspects. Participants consented, having their right to anonymity, withdrawal, confidentiality affirmed and were told their data would be analysed and potentially published. Post-completion, participants were provided an opportunity to withdraw and debriefed on research aims.</p>
</div>
<div id="results" class="section level4">
<h4><strong>Results</strong></h4>
<p>To improve internal validity <span class="citation">(Nichols &amp; Maner, 2008)</span>, participants on the QQM module (n = 31) were excluded for being aware of research aims. Individuals under 18 years old constitute a ‘vulnerable population’ for whom additional briefing and approval from guardians is necessary for informed consent <span class="citation">(British Psychological Society, 2021)</span> - since neither were assured in this study, under-18s (n = 1)were excluded from analysis. Responses with missing data (n = 1) were also excluded.</p>
<p>Exclusion in all cases involved listwise deletion (LD) of responses. Whilst this can reduce statistical power in analysis <span class="citation">(Myers, 2011)</span>, it was deemed appropriate as the number of excluded cases (n = 33) was relatively small compared to the remaining sample size (n = 642), making loss of statistical power minimal whilst also improving validity of results <span class="citation">(Kang, 2013)</span>. Alternative methods such as multiple imputation could have been used with missing data <span class="citation">(Rubin, 2004)</span>. This was deemed unnecessary as methods like multiple imputation do not impact statistical power significantly differently from LD when dealing with item-level missing data <span class="citation">(Parent, 2013)</span>, as was the case in this sample where the excluded case was missing data on just one item (QQM).</p>
<p>Inter-item correlations within a scale measuring a construct should at least exceed an “exemplary” value of |.3| <span class="citation">(Robinson, Shaver &amp; Wrightsman, 1991, p. 13)</span>. Furthermore, inter-item correlations above |.85| indicate that the two items do not measure substantially different aspects of the construct and thus largely equivalent <span class="citation">(Paulsen &amp; BrckaLorenz, 2017)</span>. Therefore, all items that either: have no inter-item correlations above |.3| or any inter-item correlations above |.85| were excluded from the analysis. These criteria excluded items 3, 14 and 23.</p>
<p>Bartlett’s test of sphericity was significant, (<span class="math inline">\(x^{2}\)</span>(231) = 5052.349 p &lt; .05) demonstrating that the correlation matrix of this data is significantly different from an identity matrix. Furthermore, a Kaiser-Meyer-Olkin test was used to produce a measure of sampling adequacy (MSA). Overall MSA was .84, with a range of .62-.92, indicating an “meritorious” overall MSA, and ranging from “mediocre” to “marvellous” <span class="citation">(Kaiser &amp; Rice, 1974, p. 112)</span>. A minimum threshold of .5 for KMO values <span class="citation">(Guttman, 1953, cited in Kaiser &amp; Rice, 1974)</span> was exceeded in all cases, suggesting all included variables are suitable for Exploratory factor analysis (EFA).</p>
<p>EFA requires predetermination of factor size <span class="citation">(Fabrigar, Wegener, MacCallum &amp; Strahan, 1999)</span>. To achieve this, a scree plot <span class="citation">(Cattell, 1966)</span> can be used. However, determining factor size from a scree plot alone is inherently subjective <span class="citation">(Courtney &amp; Gordon, 2013)</span>. Pairing it (Figure 1) with a parallel analysis (PA) <span class="citation">(Horn, 1965)</span> reduces subjectivity. PA compares eigenvalues of each factor - “the amount of variance of the variables accounted for by that factor” <span class="citation">(Norris &amp; Lecavalier, 2010, p. 9)</span> - with random eigenvalues. Identifying factor eigenvalues greater than 1 <span class="citation">(Kaiser, 1960)</span> could be the criteria used to determine factor extraction, however this can (over)underestimate the number of factors <span class="citation">(Zwick &amp; Velicer, 1986)</span>. In PA, factor and random eigenvalues are ordered and compared. The number of factor eigenvalues greater than random eigenvalues determines the suggested factor size. As seen in Figure 1, 7 factors were extracted.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>EFA used a minimum residuals (minres) method <span class="citation">(Comrey, 1962)</span>, as with PA. Factor rotation method used was oblique. Oblique rotations do not force factors to correlate as orthogonal rotations would, making the former better suited for dealing with interrelated behaviours, like DSSE self-assessments, which are already expected to correlate <span class="citation">(Osborne, 2015)</span>.</p>
<p>EFA can be iterative, involving reanalysis after exclusions of items and reduction of factor size. Furthermore, factor clustering must be thematically coherent. Such reanalysis and thematic considerations were necessary. Exclusion criteria are:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: decimal">
<li><p><strong>Significance threshold.</strong> Whilst there is no decisive view of what the minimum threshold for factor loading should be <span class="citation">(Peterson, 2000)</span>, social science favours a |.3| threshold for sample sizes greater than 350 <span class="citation">(Hair, 2019)</span>, where coefficients near |.5| are considered “practically significant.” This EFA uses this |.3| threshold to determine significance. For items which do not load significantly on any factor, it is suggested to remove items individually, assessing the factor structure after each until a stable factor structure is found (where all items have at least 1 significant factor loading) <span class="citation">(Samuels, 2017)</span>. This excluded items 7, 15, 16 and 23.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Insignificant factors.</strong> Factors with less than 3 significant item loadings are likely weak <span class="citation">(Samuels, 2017)</span>. As such, it is recommended <span class="citation">(Watkins, 2018)</span> to sequentially reduce factor size until a stable factor structure is found (all factors have at least 3 significant factor loadings). This reduced the factor size from 7 to 5.</p></li>
<li><p><strong>Thematic consistency</strong> Whilst the emergent factor structure may be sound, items can cluster into a factor without actually fitting the theme of that factor. Furthermore, items may significantly cross-load onto multiple items. Determining thematic consistency within factors is inherently subjective, however as the goal with this analysis is to discover coherent DSSE scale factors, some adjustments were made. Items 10, 13 and 25 cross-loaded and thus their primary loading was used to assign them to a factor. Item 11 also cross-loaded but coefficients were very similar (.37 &amp; .39) nor practically significant, thus it was excluded entirely.</p></li>
</ol>

<p>EFA returned 5 factors accounting for 52% of overall variance. Oblique rotation was appropriate given all factor correlations were non-zero.</p>
<p>Factors were as follows: MR1 = Appearance self esteem - including 5 items (e.g. item 9 “I try to avoid seeing my body in the mirror”); MR2 = Academic self-esteem - including 4 items (e.g. Item 17 “When I succeed on an assessment, I feel a sense of self-pride.”); MR3 = Social media self-esteem - including 3 items (e.g. Item 4 “My sense of self-worth increases when I get positive engagement on my social media”); MR4 = Health-based self-esteem - including 3 items (e.g. Item 22 “My self-esteem goes up when I am healthy”); MR5 = Social acceptance self-esteem - including 3 items (e.g. Item 1 “Knowing someone liked me would make me feel good about myself”).</p>
<p>Hu and Bentler <span class="citation">(1999)</span> suggest model fit cut-off values of either a TLI &gt; .96 &amp; SRMR &lt; .06 or RMSEA &lt; .05 and SRMR &lt; .09, these cut-offs are not absolute. Likelihood Chi square was highly significant <span class="math inline">\(x^{2}\)</span> = 209.07, p &lt; .001, likely due to the large sample size (n = 642). Tucker Lewis index was .929, SRMR was .02, and RMSEA was .054, 90% CI [.045, .063]. Evidently, this indicates poor model fit. Such a model likely has enhanced type I and II error rates <span class="citation">(Hu &amp; Bentler, 1999)</span>.</p>
<p><img src="data:image/png;base64," width="672" /></p>
<p>Reliability analysis using McDonald’s <span class="math inline">\(\omega\)</span> <span class="citation">(McDonald, 1999)</span> reported three items (9, 22 &amp; 24) with low general factor loadings, indicating a common factor model is inappropriate <span class="citation">(Field, 2022)</span>. An <span class="math inline">\(\omega\)</span> hierarchical of 0.58 was found, where items explained 35% of the variance in the general common factor, considered to be fairly low. An overall <span class="math inline">\(\omega\)</span> total of 0.9 was observed, indicating the overall scale is highly reliable. Model fit indexes (<span class="math inline">\(x^{2}\)</span> = 2130.86, p &lt; 0; RMSEA = .152, 10% CI [.146-.158]) indicated that the 5-factor model is a better fit than a single-factor model. <span class="math inline">\(\omega\)</span> totals for each sub-scale were: MR1 = .84, MR2 = .79, MR3 = .74, MR4 = .8, MR5 = .67. All sub-scales are reliable, with MR5 being the least reliable.</p>
<p>Convergent validity was tested by computing composite scores for each factor and correlating them with the GSE item scores. Divergent validity was similarly tested, but instead used OTE scores.</p>

<p>SISE and OPEN both negatively correlate with MR1, MR2, MR3 and MR5, whilst not correlating with MR4. This indicates poor convergent validity for this scale as factors composites are expected to correlate positively with GSE as it is a related construct. Poor discriminant validity was also observed for all but one factor (MR4), where factor composites are expected to not correlate with OTE as it is an unrelated construct.</p>
</div>
<div id="discussion" class="section level4">
<h4><strong>Discussion</strong></h4>
<p>Overall, inter-item correlations revealed 3 items (3, 14 &amp; 23) did not significantly correlate with any others, whilst all others were satisfactory. EFA revealed 5 coherent factors, accounting for 52% of overall variance. However, model fit indexes were slightly below recommended thresholds, suggesting type I and II error rates are enhanced in this model. Despite reliable omega values for the scale and sub-scales, some items had no significant general factor loadings and thus a common factor model is inappropriate here. Convergent and divergent validity was poor for all factors, except factor MR4 which had good discriminant validity.</p>
<p>These issues with the analysis suggest the items included and the scale itself poorly reflect the target construct. Future research could benefit from exploring alternative DSSE items in conjunction with highly performing items from this analysis (e.g. item 19) in order to produce a scale which more accurately reflects underlying DSSE constructs, providing greater practical utility than this scale.</p>
</div>
